Fill and boil your #kettle{} with water to use for the pasta. Half, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and halved). Trim, peel and coarsely grate the @cooked beetroot{250%g}. 

> TIP: Wear rubber gloves to prevent staining your hands!

Heat a splash of @oil{1%splash} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot, pop in the onion, beetroot and @British pork mince{225%g}. Season with @salt{}. Cook until the pork is beginning to brown and the onion starting to so en, ~{3-5%minutes}, breaking up the pork with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks. Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with a good pinch of @salt{}. Bring back to the boil on high heat.

Mix the @cornflour{5%g} with 1 tbsp of water per person. Stir to dissolve. Add the @smoked paprika{1%tsp} and @chilli flakes{0.1%tsp} (careful they're hot!) to the frying pan. Mix well and cook for ~{30%seconds}. Stir in the @chopped tomatoes{½%tin}(finely chopped), @water{250%ml}, dissolved cornflour, @beef stock powder{½%tsp} and @?sugar{¼%tsp} (if using). Bring to the boil, stir to dissolve the stock powder then reduce the heat to simmer.

Pop the @pappardelle{200%g} into the saucepan. Stir and boil for cook until al dente, around ~{7%minutes}.

> TIP: 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

Drain into a #colander{}. Return to the pan o  the heat and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{pinch}.

While the pasta cooks, roughly chop the @dill{1%sprig}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Taste the goulash and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if necessary. Serve the pasta in #bowls{} with the goulash spooned on top. Add a good dollop of @sour cream{75%g} and a nice sprinkling of dill. HAPPY HALLOWEEN!